Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

THE TEXAS NATIONAL GUARD JOINS THE NORTH TEXAS FOOD BANK FOR DISASTER RELIEF MOBILE PANTRY STOP AT FAIR PARK

The North Texas Food Bank (NTFB), in conjunction with the Texas National Guard, Fair Park First, Spectra, and In the City for Good, is returning to Fair Park to distribute free food on Thursday, April 16 from 9:00 AM until 12:00 PM, or until all available food has been distributed.

Thursday, April 16 from 9:00 AM â€“ 12:00 PM, or until all available food has been distributed. Food pantry guestâ€™s vehicles will not be allowed to enter the Fair Park grounds until 8:15 AM or later.

The pick-up location will be in Lots 5A and 6A, located in between Robert B Cullum Boulevard and 2nd Avenue inside Fair Park. Participants should enter through Gate 5 only, located at the intersection of Robert B Cullum Boulevard and Grand Avenue. The Dallas Police Department will be onsite to assist with traffic flow.

Please bring your ID!

Visit www.ntfb.org/mobile-pantry for information on other NTFB Disaster Relief Mobile Pantry events.

post_text:
On Thursday, October 24, students can wear ORANGE in support of Bullying Prevention and Unity Day. Together, we are united for kindness, acceptance and inclusion. Students can wear jeans ONLY if they wear an ORANGE shirt. No money is required for this day.

There will also be two assemblies with a very special guest speaker, Mr. Mateo Magdaleno, who speaks on anti-bullying and acceptance of others to teens and pre-teens all across our nation.

Middle School assembly will be at 10:00 a.m. in the gymnasium.
4th grade & 5th grade assembly will be at 1:00 p.m. in the gymnasium.

Anyone is welcome to attend and can park across the street at the rec center.

post_text: Threat Incident Update:
text: Threat Incident Update:

post_text:
Update:
A former student made a threat towards the campus for Monday. We immediately notified law enforcement and right after notifying law enforcement, we immediately sent out this communication to parents. Since the former student has been identified, we aren't able to comment further while law enforcement addresses this matter over the weekend. Your children's safety is our highest priority, as soon as we have additional information, we will update this post.
*******************************************

Dear parents:

A short time ago, we made aware of a threat made against East Grand Preparatory and immediately notified law enforcement. Law enforcement is actively investigating and are working closely with them. At this time, school will be held next week with no interruptions. We are asking law enforcement to be present at school as appropriate.

If anyone knows of any further information on this matter, please contact Ms. Sonya Webb, principal at 214-824-4747 or at swebb@cityscapeschools.org.

We will have Visual Art classes, Folklorico, and Theater. A professional artist will teach each class. The cost is only $15 each month per class. Students can enroll in more than one class.

The after-school hours will be 3:40 â€“ 4:40 Monday, Tuesday and Thursday

text: Carpool Time!

post_text:
Hello Parents!

On Friday's we have EGP Spirit day. Student's may wear their EGP Spirit shirt with the approved uniform pants/skirt. No jeans will be allowed! No exceptions!

Carpool Reminders:

ONLY pick up for Pre-K will be allowed in the carpool line between 2:30 pm and 3:00 pm to pick up.
On Monday parents will not be able to walk their children to and from their classes. You will only be able to use the carpool lines.
In the morning during carpool drop off, we will have teacher aids that will be escorting the younger children inside the school.
Parents that do not have a car and walk with their students will still follow the same pickup rules as cars in the carpool line for either green or blue pick up.
If you have an older student and a younger student, your pick up time will be the time that the older students get out of school.
Thank you again for your patience as we continue to improve the carpool lines.

Go Eagles!

post_text:
Parents and Guardians,

We are excited to see everyone back at school tomorrow! Please be on time and arrive by 7:40 am. We will allow you to walk your child(ren) to their class/holding area during the first week only. Starting the second week you will have to use the carpool lane. We will have staff members and student helpers assist your child in their class/ holding area at that time.

We ask you not have lunch with your child(ren) on the first two weeks of school so that they may develop an understanding of the routines and procedures for lunch. This typically affects our younger students the most. When mom and/or dad each lunch with them they tend to want to go home!

Finally, please stay in your car during afternoon carpool pickup.

We look forward to another successful year with your student!

Sincerely,

Mrs. Webb, Principal

Time: 3:45pm-5:00pm

Where: EGP Gym

Thank you! We are looking forward to another great volleyball season at EGP!

In order to keep your child's mind active and engaged, The Dallas City of Learning has a variety of free learning opportunities for students ranging from Coding and Gaming workshops, Earth and Science Summer programs, and Sports camps.

To learn more about these and many other opportunities please visit https://dallascityoflearning.org/

post_text:
Spread the Word About Summer Meals!

Come to EGP for breakfast and lunch Monday-Friday until June 28th. This program serves a vital need for hard-working families that rely upon federally funded nutrition programs during the school year. Access to meals sites during the summer fills the budget gap for those families by providing free meals to youth through 18 years of age. Texas has one of the lowest Summer Meals participation rates in the United States simply because kids and teens don't know about it. Help us spread the word so they can spend the summer having fun, not being hungry!
